spans.text: to rouse the sounding string THE POET OF MY GOD — Awake my glory
High over yonder azure Heaven's exalted dome By mortal eye unkenned — where East nor West Nor South , nor blustering North has breath to blow
East nor West Nor South , nor blustering North
that nor in Presence or in Power Shines He less perfect here
her pathless walk , studious to view Thy works of vaster fabric
the spangled sky Measures her pathless walk , studious to view Thy works of vaster fabric , where the Planets

with outstretched arm Kerb the wild winds and discipline the billows , The suppliant Sailor finds Thee there , his chief , His only help — When Thou rebukest the storm — It ceases — and the vessel gently glides Along the glassy level of the calm

thy mines Gani or Raolconda she arrive , And from the adamant's imperial blaze Form weak ideas of her Maker's glory
weak ideas of her Maker's glory
undermine the treasure-fertile womb Of the huge Pyrenean , to detect The Agat and the deep-intrenched gem Of kindred Jasper — Nature in them both Delights to play the Mimic on herself
to play the Mimic on herself

thundering down In desperate cascade with flowers and beasts And all the living landskip of the vale : In vain thy pencil Claudio , or Poussin , Or thine , immortal Guido , would essay Such skill to imitate — it is the hand Of God himself — for God himself is there
beds of magnets , minerals , and spar

unless the oak His lordly head uprears , and branching arms
liberty her utmost scope to range , Turn we to yonder enclosures , where appears Chequered variety in all her forms , Which the vague mind attract and still suspend With sweet perplexity
that tall beech Her pensile house the feathered Artist builds — The rocking winds molest her not
call Correggio , or let Titian come To paint the hawthorn's bloom
come To paint the hawthorn's bloom
Go call Correggio , or let Titian come To paint the hawthorn's bloom , or teach the cherry To blush with just vermilion — hence away — Hence you profane ! for God himself
the Artificer Divine — And though nor shining sun , nor twinkling star Bedecked the crimson curtains of the sky
the crimson curtains of the sky
in that frame So fearfully , so wonderfully made
